        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My Thermador column is warm but the lights and LCD still work",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Means the control system is alive but the refrigeration circuit isn't starting. Three common causes: failed compressor start relay ($85–$145 part), failed overload protector ($65–$125), or a failed inverter board (Freedom columns use variable-speed inverter compressors — board replacement $580–$920). Diagnostic watches compressor voltage and current at startup, isolates which component failed. 50% of 'warm column, controls work' calls resolve with a relay or overload replacement — the expensive inverter board is the minority."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Thermador wine column repair cost as much as refrigerator repair?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Usually a bit less. Wine columns (T18IW, T24IW, VCH series legacy) run at higher cavity temperatures (45–64°F vs. 35–38°F) so their compressors and defrost systems see less stress. Typical wine column repairs: control board $520–$780, compressor $850–$1,350, evaporator fan $285–$380, humidity sensor $195–$265. Less common than refrigerator column failures — these units see lighter service loads."
